Tutorial

Tutorial 1 - Revisiting Javascript

12 steps

In this tutorial, revisit Javascript and explore new concepts such as asynchronous functions and handling errors effectively. Learn about promises and how to properly handle multiples of them in different situations. Explore more about types and when to convert between data types.

For technical help on the StackUp platform & quest-related questions, join our Discord, head to the 🆘 | quest-help-forum channel and look for the correct thread to ask your question.

Join us on Discord

Helpful prior knowledge

No prior programming experience needed but recommended to have some experience with Javascript.

Learning Outcomes

You will be able to:

  • Learn Javascript using Deno
  • Write basic Javascript syntax
  • Handle promises in Javascript

Tutorial Steps

Total steps: 12

  • Step 4: Variables in Javascript

    Let's freshen up and learn Javascript variables. First, create a directory called javascript. Next, head to the javascript directory and create a file called variables.js. Finally, write a comment with the following syntax on top of the variables.js file.

    // Variables in Javascript
    JavaScript

    A comment in Javascript starts with //.

    Javascript variables can be declared with both var, let and const keywords.

    However, be reminded that each keyword works differently, both in scope and mutability. Append the following code below the first line.

    // Variables in Javascript

let foo1 = "Hi";

{
  var foo2 = "Hello";
  let foo1 = "Goodbye!";
  const foo3 = "I am only here"
  let foo4 = "I am only here as well"
}

// But foo3 and foo4 cannot be called here.
console.log(foo1, foo2, foo3, foo4)
    JavaScript

    Now, run the following command at the root directory of your project.

    deno run javascript/variables.js

    The command should give you an error similar to the screenshot below.

    Let's understand why this happens.

    1. Javascript supports block-syntax – statements can be grouped and enclosed within brackets { and }.
    2. Statements within a block have a different scope. Scope means the availability of a name such as variables and functions within a limited namespace. This means statements within and outside a block have different scoping.
    3. foo1 and foo2 are globally scoped. The var keyword allows variables in any statement within or outside block-syntax to be globally scoped.
    4. foo1 is globally scoped because it's at the top-most part of the namespace and not within any block-syntax or function.
    5. foo3 and foo4 are locally scoped. This means they are only bound within the block and not outside of it.

    Because of this, foo3 and foo4 variables are undefined since they are only defined within a block-syntax. Hence, the reference error, "foo3 is not defined". Changing the line

    // But foo3 and foo4 cannot be called here.
console.log(foo1, foo2, foo3, foo4)
    JavaScript

    to

    // But foo3 and foo4 cannot be called here.
console.log(foo1, foo2)
    JavaScript

    will allow the code to run correctly once you run the following command again.

    deno run javascript/variables.js

    The command should output "Hi Hello".

    At this point, your directory structure should look similar to the screenshot below.

  • Step 5: Data Types in Javascript

    Javascript is a dynamically typed and weakly typed language. It's a dynamic language since variables can be assigned or reassigned with values of all types.

    Head to the javascript directory and create a new file called data-types.js. Write the following code to your new file data-types.js.

    let variable = "foo";  // this is a string
variable = 0;  // variable is reassigned as a number
variable = false;  // variable is reassigned as a boolean
    JavaScript

    It's also weakly typed because values of different types are implicitly coerced into another type, also called implicit type coercion. Take for example the following code snippet.

    let foo = variable + 12;
foo = foo + " this is twelve and ";
foo = foo + 0;
console.log(foo);
    JavaScript

    Copy and append the new code above to your data-types.js file. Run the following command.

    deno run ./javascript/data-types.js

    It should output "12 this is twelve and 0" on the terminal.

    ️️Be careful when operating with values in Javascript, especially when using operands. For example, consider the following code snippet and code behaviour between subtraction and addition operands.

    const foo2 = "11";
console.log("With subtraction: ", foo2 - 2);
console.log("With addition: ", foo2 + 2);
    JavaScript

    This will have the output

    With subtraction:  9
With addition:  112

    on your terminal.

    This is a notorious pitfall in Javascript that plagues the language until today. To avoid such issues where a developer gets incorrect types for inputs, one might use the typeof keyword to identify the type. For example, the following code snippet below uses a conditional block in a function to check the type of a parameter.

    function addATrueNumber(x, y) {
  if ((typeof x === "number") && (typeof y === "number")) {
    return x + y;
  }
  throw new Error("One of the inputs is not a number", {
    cause: "Not a number.",
  });
}

const aTrueNumber = addATrueNumber(12, 12);
console.log(aTrueNumber);
    JavaScript

    Using the same function, inputting numbers but string values will result in an error. For example, the following code snippet will throw an error.

    const notATrueNumber = addATrueNumber(12, "12");
    JavaScript

    Run the following command at the root directory of your project to observe its behaviour.

    deno run ./javascript/data-types.js

    Your error will look similar to the screenshot below.

    The full code for data-types.js is shown below.

    let variable = "foo"; // this is a string
variable = 0; // variable is reassigned as a number
variable = false; // variable is reassigned as a boolean
variable = 0.1; // variable is reassigned as a number

let foo = variable + 12;
foo = foo + " this is twelve and ";
foo = foo + 0;
console.log(foo);

const foo2 = "11";
console.log("With subtraction: ", foo2 - 2);
console.log("With addition: ", foo2 + 2);

function addATrueNumber(x, y) {
  if ((typeof x === "number") && (typeof y === "number")) {
    return x + y;
  }
  throw new Error("One of the inputs is not a number", {
    cause: "Not a number.",
  });
}

const aTrueNumber = addATrueNumber(12, 12);
console.log(aTrueNumber);
const notATrueNumber = addATrueNumber(12, "12");
    JavaScript

    Try experimenting and exploring around and share what you think about the issues of the types in Javascript in our Discord forum channel.

  • Step 6: Data Structures in Javascript

    Javascript has a primitive data structure called objects. An object in Javascript is a mutable value. Most data such as numbers, strings, dictionaries, and arrays in Javascript are objects including its data types and functions.

    They are objects because they contain a collection of properties such as methods and object members. Methods are functions unique to an object and object members are either key-value pairs or a method for an object.

    Head to the javascript directory and create a new file called data-structures.js. Write the following code to your new file data-structures.js.

    const x = [1, 2]; // an array
const y = {
  key: "pair",
  date: new Date(),
  generateDate() {
    this.date = new Date();
  },
}; // a key-value pair or a dictionary or object

console.log(x, typeof x);
console.log(y, typeof y);
y.generateDate();
console.log(y);
    JavaScript

    Run the following command at the root directory of your project to observe its behaviour.

    deno run ./javascript/data-structures.js

    The code is an example that both array x and dictionary y are both objects. Most learners find this confusing at first but both have the same set of primitive properties and methods, for example, the .valueOf() method, hence, most data and values in Javascript are also objects.

    You didn't set this. The language already has this set automatically.

    Since most of your Javascript journey is manipulating objects around, most developers just extend and wrap around existing object wrappers, or create custom objects with custom object members. For example, consider the following code snippet.

    let person = {};
person.age = 20;
person.name = {};
person.name.first = "John";
person.name.last = "River";
person.name.updateFirstName = function (x) {
  this.first = x;
};
console.log(person);
person.name.updateFirstName("Jonathan");
console.log(person);
    JavaScript

    The code shows how to extend and further set up object members such as adding a function that updates the first name of the person object. age, name, name.first, name.last and name.updateFirstName are object members of variable and object person. You might notice that this is also a nested object since .name property itself is an object.

    Run the following command at the root directory of your project to observe its behaviour.

    deno run ./javascript/data-structures.js

    The full code for data-structures.js is shown below.

    const x = [1, 2]; // an array
const y = {
  key: "pair",
  date: new Date(),
  generateDate() {
    this.date = new Date();
  },
}; // a key-value pair or a dictionary or object

console.log(x, typeof x);
console.log(y, typeof y);
y.generateDate();
console.log(y);

const person = {};
person.age = 20;
person.name = {};
person.name.first = "John";
person.name.last = "River";
person.name.updateFirstName = function (x) {
  this.first = x;
};
console.log(person);
person.name.updateFirstName("Jonathan");
console.log(person);
    JavaScript
  • Step 7: Conditionals in Javascript

    This short step mentions conditionals in Javascript. Like most languages, Javascript has the concepts of truthy and falsy values. The most notable is true and false and they are of type boolean.

    Most commonly used comparison operations are == for equality, === for strong equality which also compares the type of data e.g. number vs string, > for greater than, < for less than, >= for greater than or equal to, <= for less than or equal to and lastly, ! for the "logical not" operator which negates a boolean value e.g. true becomes false.

    Head to the javascript directory. Create a new file called conditionals.js.

    Write the following code snippet to conditionals.js.

    const veryTrue = true;
const veryFalse = false;

if (veryTrue) {
  console.log("Very True");
}

if (!veryFalse) {
  console.log("Very False");
}
    JavaScript

    The code just assigns true and false values to two variables. You can see here a conditional "if" block statement used. Enclosed within () after the if keyword is the predicate, the condition that needs to be evaluated whether to proceed within the "if" block or the "else" block. However, the "else" block is not evident here but evident in the next code snippet as you read further below.

    Run the following command at the root directory of your project to observe its behaviour.

    deno run ./javascript/conditionals.js

    Append the following code snippet to conditionals.js.

    function divide(x, y) {
  if (y === 0) {
    throw new Error(
      `Division by zero. Tried to operate ${x} with divisor ${y}.`,
      { cause: "Division by zero." },
    );
  }
  return x / y;
}

try {
  const quotient1 = divide(100, 10);
  const quotient2 = divide(10, 0);
  console.log(quotient1, quotient2);
} catch (err) {
  if (err instanceof Error) {
    console.error(err.message);
  } else {
    console.error(`Unknown error ${err}.`);
  }
}
    JavaScript

    This example shows how to handle errors with the try-catch block statement in Javascript, and how to write a divide function that throws a "division by zero" error since in Javascript, "division by zero" does not throw an error but returns a special number value called Infinity. A sample of what it looks like is shown on the following screenshot of the Deno REPL below.

    Run the following command at the root directory of your project to observe its behaviour.

    deno run ./javascript/conditionals.js

    So far, you have learned to use conditionals with "if" or "if-else" block statements.

    You also got a usage example of the instanceof operator which checks if an object matches a type or class object, a prototype.

    In some cases, you prefer using a switch-case block statement instead of an if-else block statement.. Here is an example for using a switch-case, write the following code snippet to conditionals.js.

    switch (!veryFalse) {
  case false:
    console.log("False");
    break;
  case true:
    console.log("True");
    break;
  default:
    console.error(veryFalse);
}

const x = "w";
switch (x) {
  case "wow":
    console.log(x);
    break;
  case 2:
    console.log(x);
    break;
  default:
    throw new Error("Not 2 or wow.");
}
    JavaScript

    Switch statements will evaluate the predicate within () after the switch keyword. Each case keyword should follow a possible case or "value" to run a specific statement e.g. outputting something with console.log. You can even remove the break keyword so it can also check other possible cases as well below the previous case. But that is highly discouraged and might be the source of bugs in your code.

    An optional default keyword can be used to run code when all cases don't match.

    Run the following command at the root directory of your project to observe its behaviour.

    deno run ./javascript/conditionals.js

    The full code for conditionals.js is shown below.

    const veryTrue = true;
const veryFalse = false;

if (veryTrue) {
  console.log("Very True");
}

if (!veryFalse) {
  console.log("Very False");
}

function divide(x, y) {
  if (y === 0) {
    throw new Error(
      `Division by zero. Tried to operate ${x} with divisor ${y}.`,
      { cause: "Division by zero." },
    );
  }
  return x / y;
}

try {
  const quotient1 = divide(100, 10);
  const quotient2 = divide(10, 0);
  console.log(quotient1, quotient2);
} catch (err) {
  if (err instanceof Error) {
    console.error(err.message);
  } else {
    console.error(`Unknown error ${err}.`);
  }
}

switch (!veryFalse) {
  case false:
    console.log("False");
    break;
  case true:
    console.log("True");
    break;
  default:
    console.error(veryFalse);
}

const x = "w";
switch (x) {
  case "wow":
    console.log(x);
    break;
  case 2:
    console.log(x);
    break;
  default:
    throw new Error("Not 2 or wow.");
}
    JavaScript
  • Step 8: Loops in Javascript

    Loops in Javascript come in variants. The classic for loop, the while loop, the do-while loop, the for-in loop, the for-of loop and the forEach() method.

    Loops are quite useful for iterating over a collection of data, usually data inside of arrays. It is also useful for running n times of the same block of code.

    For example, a classic for loop is pretty useful for repetitive execution at a specific number of times. Head to the javascript directory and create a new file called loops.js. Write the following code to loops.js.

    const MAX = 10;
for (let i = 0; i < MAX; i++) {
	console.log(i);
}
    JavaScript

    Here, you have set three statements within the () parentheses. The first is the initialization statement, where it is executed once e.g. to initialize and define a counter variable i. The second is the predicate or condition similar to how you write an if-else block statement; this is evaluated before each iteration. The third statement is what's executed after each iteration e.g. to modify the counter variable.

    Run the following command at the root directory of your project to observe its behaviour.

    deno run ./javascript/loops.js

    You can also do the same thing with a while loop. Append and write the following code.

    let d = 0;
while (d < MAX) {
	console.log(d);
	d++;
}
    JavaScript

    You can see a similarity between if-else block statement and the while loop. But in a while loop, the code inside the block will execute as long as the predicate holds true i.e. d < MAX.

    You can also write this with a do-while loop. Append and write the following code.

    d = 0;
do {
  console.log(d);
  d++;
} while (d < MAX);
    JavaScript

    All three loops are valid and quite useful when iterating over values such as array indices or running the same code n times where n is a number.

    In another example, users tend to use the classic for loop to iterate over an array similar to the code below.

    const arr = [1, 2, 3];
for (let i = 0; i < arr.length; i++) {
  console.log(i, arr[i]);
}
    JavaScript

    Fortunately, there is a better way and that is by using the for-in loop. The syntax is cleaner and easier to understand. It's useful to iterate over the properties (keys) of an object. You can replace the previous for loop with the following code.

    for (const key in arr) {
  console.log(key, arr[key]);
}
    JavaScript

    You can also just use the for-of loop variant when you want to just iterate over the values.

    for (const val of arr) {
  console.log(val);
}
    JavaScript

    Lastly, collections such as arrays and strings have a forEach method that you can use if you prefer the functional programming syntax. Here is what it should look like when using the same variable arr with forEach. 

    arr.forEach((x) => console.log(x));
    JavaScript

    This might not be considered a loop since it's a method, but it's quite useful if you prefer using this over a loop.

    Loops can use the continue and break keywords to continue and break loop iteration. For example, the following code below shows how to use the two keywords.

    for (const val of arr) {
  if (val >= 2) {
    console.log("Break here");
    break;
  }
}

const arr2 = [25, 100, 50, 150];

for (const val of arr2) {
  if (val === 100) {
    console.log("Continue if 100");
    continue;
  } else if (val === 50) {
    console.log("Break if 50");
    break;
  }
}
    JavaScript

    Run the following command at the root directory of your project to observe its behaviour.

    deno run ./javascript/loops.js

    The only issue is that you cannot use the continue and break keywords to manipulate the iteration bound by the forEach method. Fortunately, loops inside the forEach method can still use the continue and break keywords. For example, consider the following code below.

    const arr3 = [10, 15, 2, 12, 26];
arr3.forEach((x) => {
  console.log(`Max iterations for i variable to cover: ${x}`);
  for (let i = 0; i < x; i++) {
    const i2 = i * 2;
    if (i2 > 5) {
      console.log("Break here!");
      console.log(`Value of i before break: ${i}`);
      break;
    } else if ((i % 2) === 0) {
      console.log("Continuing here!");
      continue;
    }
  }
});
    JavaScript

    Run the following command at the root directory of your project to observe its behaviour.

    deno run ./javascript/loops.js

    The full code for loops.js is shown below.

for (let i = 0; i < MAX; i++) {
  console.log(i);
}

while (d < MAX) {
  console.log(d);
  d++;
}

do {
  console.log(d);

} while (d < MAX);

  console.log(i, arr[i]);
}

  console.log(key, arr[key]);
}

}

  }
}

    console.log("Break if 50");
    break;
  }
}

      break;
    } else if ((i % 2) === 0) {

  • Step 9: Promises in Javascript

    In JavaScript, Promises are used to handle asynchronous operations, allowing you to perform tasks like reading files, making API calls, or fetching data from a server without blocking the execution of the rest of your code. A Promise represents a value that may be available now, or in the future, or never.

    A Promise has three possible states:

    1. Pending: The initial state; neither resolved nor rejected.

    2. Fulfilled: The operation completed successfully, and the result is available.

    3. Rejected: The operation failed, and the error is available.

    A Promise is created using the new Promise() constructor. It takes an executor function that has two parameters: resolve and reject.

    let promise = new Promise(function(resolve, reject) {
    // Asynchronous operation
    if (/* some condition */) {
        resolve('Success');  // Resolve the promise if the operation is successful
    } else {
        reject('Failure');   // Reject the promise if the operation fails
    }
});
    JavaScript

    Head to the javascript directory and create a new file called promises.js. Write the following code to promises.js.

    let promise = new Promise(function(resolve, reject) {
    let success = true;  // Change this to false to test the rejection

    if (success) {
        resolve('Operation was successful!');
    } else {
        reject('Operation failed.');
    }
});
    JavaScript

    In this example, you are using the Promise() constructor to create a Promise object. When writing the new object with a new keyword, the constructor must receive a function, namely an executor. The function must receive two parameters: resolveFunc and rejectFunc. Based on the name, these two functions are run whenever a specific condition is met, usually defined by the programmer.

    Here is an example of writing a custom promise-based timeout. Write this code to promises.js.

    /*
 * Handrolled version of setTimeOut.
 */
const customSetTimeOut = (x) =>
  new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
    if ((typeof x) !== "number") {
      const errorVal = new Error("Not a number", {
        cause: "Value is not a number.",
      });
      return reject({
        errorVal,
        value: x,
      });
    } else {
      const currentTime = new Date();
      const previousSeconds = currentTime.getTime();
      const fullFilledSeconds = previousSeconds + (x * 1000);

      let newTime = new Date();
      do {
        newTime = new Date();
      } while (newTime.getTime() < fullFilledSeconds + 1);
      return resolve(`Finished the ${x} seconds countdown!`);
    }
  });

customSetTimeOut("2 ").then((x) => console.log(x)).catch((err) => {
  console.error(err);
  console.log("Attempting to convert string to a number value!");
  // If it's not a number, set the timeout to 0. This just serves as an example.
  const number = !isNaN(err.value.trim())
    ? Number.parseInt(err.value.trim())
    : 0;
  customSetTimeOut(number); // we will not handle the error here for now
  console.log(`Conversion successful. Timeout lasted in ${number} seconds`);
});
    JavaScript

    Experiment between stringified digits vs actual number values on the function by replacing "2 " with actual number value 2.

    Run the following command at the root directory of your project to observe its behaviour.

    deno run ./javascript/promises.js

    The full code for promises.js is shown below.

    let promise = new Promise(function (resolve, reject) {
  let success = true; // Change this to false to test the rejection

  if (success) {
    resolve("Operation was successful!");
  } else {
    reject("Operation failed.");
  }
});

console.log(await promise);

  customSetTimeOut("2 ").then((x) => console.log(x)).catch((err) => {
	console.error(err);
	console.log("Attempting to convert string to a number value!");
	// If it's not a number, set the timeout to 0. This just serves as an example.
	const number = !isNaN(err.value.trim())
	  ? Number.parseInt(err.value.trim())
	  : 0;
	customSetTimeOut(number); // we will not handle the error here for now
	console.log(`Conversion successful. Timeout lasted in ${number} seconds`);
  });
    JavaScript

    But what if you are to handle multiple promises? Let's do that in the next step.

  • Step 10: Handling Multiple Promises in Javascript

    When handling multiple data that needs to be processed asynchronously, the common pitfall is the wrong choice of a loop variant in Javascript.

    Head to the javascript directory and create a new file called multiple-promises.js. Write the following code to your new file.

    const arr = [];
for (let i = 2; i < 100; i+=2) {
  const promise = new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
    if ((i % 2) === 0) {
      return resolve(i + 2);
    }
    return reject(-100);
  });
  arr.push(promise);
}

console.log(arr);
    JavaScript

    This part of the code generates an array containing promise objects that should be awaited.

    Run the following command at the root directory of your project to observe its behaviour.

    deno run ./javascript/multiple-promises.js

    Usually, beginners will await each promise object of an array which can lead to performance issues and slows down your program such as this code below.

    for (const element of arr) {
  const val = await element;
  console.log(val);
}
    JavaScript

    This code is small to notice the difference but in huge code bases dealing thousands of data, this difference can be exponential. Therefore, it is wrong to await each promise from an array of promise objects.

    Fortunately, there is a more efficient way. Using the for-await loop, you can avoid performance penalties by fully utilising the asynchronous code. Replacing the previous for loop with the code below is the correct approach.

    for await (const element of arr) {
  console.log(element);
}
    JavaScript

    You can even use the following as well by fully using the Promise methods such as Promise.all before processing the data synchronously.

    Promise.all(arr).then((values) => {
  values.forEach((value) => console.log("From Promise.all", value));
}).catch((err) => console.error(err));
    JavaScript

    The full code for multiple-promises.js is shown below.

    const arr = [];
for (let i = 2; i < 100; i+=2) {
  const promise = new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
    if ((i % 2) === 0) {
      return resolve(i + 2);
    }
    return reject(-100);
  });
  arr.push(promise);
}

console.log(arr);

for (const element of arr) {
  const val = await element;
  console.log(val);
}

for await (const element of arr) {
  console.log(element);
}

Promise.all(arr).then((values) => {
  values.forEach((value) => console.log("From Promise.all", value));
}).catch((err) => console.error(err));
    JavaScript

    Run the following command at the root directory of your project to observe its behaviour.

    deno run ./javascript/multiple-promises.js
  • Step 11: Object Oriented Programming In Javascript

    Javascript is an Object-Oriented Programming language or OOP. With the introduction of classes, one can define a class to create objects and apply inheritance.

    Head to the javascript directory and create a new file called oop.js. Write the following code to oop.js.

    class Animal {
  constructor(name) {
    if (name === undefined) return this.name = "Unknown";
    return this.name = name;
  }
}

const newAnimal = new Animal("Weird");
console.log(newAnimal);
    JavaScript

    Run the following command at the root directory of your project to observe its behaviour.

    deno run ./javascript/oop.js

    This should output similar to the screenshot below.

    Since OOP has concepts of inheritance, one can extend the Animal class for another class and inherit the Animal class properties. Consider the following code snippet below.

    class Mammal extends Animal {
  constructor(name, genus, species) {
    super(name);
    if (genus === undefined || species === undefined) {
      throw new Error("No species added.", { cause: "Invalid input." });
    } else {
      this.genus = genus;
      this.species = species;
    }
    this.classification = "Mammalia";
  }
  getSpecies() {
    console.log(`${this.genus} ${this.species}`);
  }
}

const human = new Mammal("Stackie", "Homo", "sapiens");
console.log(human.name);
human.getSpecies();
    JavaScript

    You can see here that the Mammal class also gains the same name property from the Animal class through inheritance. However, users should keep in mind not to forget to call the super-class when constructing the class object, in this case, the Animal class, by using the super keyword as initialising the class is necessary for the subclass Mammal to work.

    To hide some properties of a class as private, one can prepend the # symbol before a property. For example, let's create a new subclass Reptile and privatise the genus property. You will only know the genus because of the getSpecies method but you still cannot access it directly.

    class Reptile extends Animal {
  #genus;
  constructor(name, genus, species) {
    super(name);
    if (genus === undefined || species === undefined) {
      throw new Error("No species added.", { cause: "Invalid input." });
    } else {
      this.#genus = genus;
      this.species = species;
    }
    this.classification = "Reptilia";
  }
  getSpecies() {
    console.log(`${this.#genus} ${this.species}`);
  }
}

const crocodile = new Reptile("Angel", "Crocodylus", "novaeguineae");
console.log(crocodile.#genus); // this will error. experiment by removing this line.
crocodile.getSpecies();
    JavaScript
